{{Infobox person | name = Julia Ann Wilbur | image = Julia Wilbur.jpg | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = August 8, 1815 | birth_place = [[Milan, New York]] | death_date = June 6, 1895<ref>Nunda Newspaper, June 1895</ref> | death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]] | resting_place_coordinates = | occupation = Nurse, Suffragist, Abolitionist | parents = {{plainlist| * Stephen Wilbur * Mary Lapham }} | }} '''Julia Wilbur''' (August 8, 1815 – June 6, 1895) was a [[Quaker]] [[abolitionist]], [[suffragist]] and nurse. She kept a diary during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] and in it she records events of historical significance as well as everyday happenings that provide a picture into life during that time.<ref name="paulawhitacre.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.paulawhitacre.com/about-julia-wilbur/|title=About Julia Wilbur|website=Paula Tarnapol Whitacre}}</ref> She is noted to have worked alongside [[Susan B. Anthony]] to establish voting rights for women. She was an early member and later secretary of the Rochester Ladies' Anti-Slavery Society which helped fund Frederick Douglass' newspaper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/c/clementsmss/umich-wcl-M-2084roc?byte=11201599;focusrgn=bioghist;subview=standard;view=reslist|title=Rochester Ladies' Anti-Slavery Society papers 1851-1868|website=quod.lib.umich.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/53277938/julia-ann-wilbur|title=Julia Ann Wilbur (1815-1895) - Find A Grave...|website=www.findagrave.com}}</ref>
== Early life and education == Julia Ann Wilbur was born on August 8, 1815 in [[Milan, New York]], the third child of Stephen Wilbur and Mary Lapham. She attended [[Oakwood Friends School|Nine Partners Boarding School]] in [[Dutchess County, New York]] from 1829 to 1831. Her mother died in 1835 and her father soon after remarried. She remained at home helping to raise her siblings before she moved to [[Rochester, New York]] to become a teacher.<ref name="paulawhitacre.com"/>
